            <div id="cite-apa" class="tab selected" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-0" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_apa rendering_contributiontobookanthology rendering_apa rendering_contributiontobookanthology_apa">van den Brandt, A., Christopher, M., Zangwill, L. M., Rezapour, J., Bowd, C., Baxter, S. L., Welsbie, D. S., Camp, A., Moghimi, S., Do, J. L., Weinreb, R. N.<a rel="Person" href="https://research.tue.nl/en/persons/chris-cp-snijders/" class="link"><span>, Snijders, C. C. P.</span></a>, &amp; Westenberg, M. A. (2020). <a rel="ContributionToBookAnthology" href="https://research.tue.nl/en/publications/glance-visual-analytics-for-monitoring-glaucoma-progression/" class="link"><span>GLANCE: Visual Analytics for Monitoring Glaucoma Progression</span></a>. In B. Kozlikova, M. Krone, N. Smit, D. W. Fellner, W. Hansmann, W. Purgathofer, &amp; F. Sillion (Eds.), <em>EG VCBM 2020 - Eurographics Workshop on Visual Computing for Biology and Medicine, Full and Short Paper Proceedings </em>(pp. 85-96). Eurographics Association. <a onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank','noopener,noreferrer'); return false;" href="https://doi.org/10.2312/vcbm.20201175" class="link"><span>https://doi.org/10.2312/vcbm.20201175</span></a></div>
            </div>
        
            <div id="cite-author" class="tab " role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-1" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_author rendering_contributiontobookanthology rendering_author rendering_contributiontobookanthology_author">van den Brandt, A. ; Christopher, Mark ; Zangwill, Linda M. et al. / <a rel="ContributionToBookAnthology" href="https://research.tue.nl/en/publications/glance-visual-analytics-for-monitoring-glaucoma-progression/" class="link"><span><strong>GLANCE : Visual Analytics for Monitoring Glaucoma Progression</strong></span></a>. EG VCBM 2020 - Eurographics Workshop on Visual Computing for Biology and Medicine, Full and Short Paper Proceedings. editor / Barbora Kozlikova ; Michael Krone ; Noeska Smit ; Dieter W. Fellner ; Werner Hansmann ; Werner Purgathofer ; Francois Sillion. Eurographics Association, 2020. pp. 85-96</div>
            </div>
        
            <div id="cite-BIBTEX" class="tab " role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-2" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_bibtex rendering_contributiontobookanthology rendering_bibtex rendering_contributiontobookanthology_bibtex"><div>@inproceedings{85edc06a4b0a41da90cbc331ad657c03,</div><div>  title     = "GLANCE: Visual Analytics for Monitoring Glaucoma Progression",</div><div>  abstract  = "Deep learning is increasingly used in the field of glaucoma research. Although deep learning models can achieve high accuracy, issues with trust, interpretability, and practical utility form barriers to adoption in clinical practice. In this study, we explore whether and how visualizations of deep learning-based measurements can be used for glaucoma management in the clinic. Through iterative design sessions with ophthalmologists, vision researchers, and manufacturers of optical coherence tomography (OCT) instruments, we distilled four main tasks, and designed a visualization tool that incorporates a visual field (VF) prediction model to provide clinical decision support in managing glaucoma progression. The tasks are: (1) assess reliability of a prediction, (2) understand why the model made a prediction, (3) alert to features that are relevant, and (4) guide future scheduling of VFs. Our approach is novel in that it considers utility of the system in a clinical context where time is limited. With use cases and a pilot user study, we demonstrate that our approach can aid clinicians in clinical management decisions and obtain appropriate trust in the system. Taken together, our work shows how visual explanations of automated methods can augment clinicians' knowledge and calibrate their trust in DL-based measurements during clinical decision making.",</div><div>  author    = "\{van den Brandt\}, A. and Mark Christopher and Zangwill, \{Linda M.\} and Jasmin Rezapour and Christopher Bowd and Baxter, \{Sally L.\} and Welsbie, \{Derek S.\} and Andrew Camp and Sasan Moghimi and Do, \{Jiun L.\} and Weinreb, \{Robert N.\} and Snijders, \{Chris C.P.\} and Westenberg, \{Michel A.\}",</div><div>  year      = "2020",</div><div>  doi       = "10.2312/vcbm.20201175",</div><div>  language  = "English",</div><div>  pages     = "85--96",</div><div>  editor    = "Barbora Kozlikova and Michael Krone and Noeska Smit and Fellner, \{Dieter W.\} and Werner Hansmann and Werner Purgathofer and Francois Sillion",</div><div>  booktitle = "EG VCBM 2020 - Eurographics Workshop on Visual Computing for Biology and Medicine, Full and Short Paper Proceedings",</div><div>  publisher = "Eurographics Association",</div><div>  note      = "2020 Eurographics Workshop on Visual Computing for Biology and Medicine, VCBM 2020 ; Conference date: 28-09-2020 Through 01-10-2020",</div><p>}</p></div>
            </div>
        
            <div id="cite-harvard" class="tab " role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-3" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_harvard rendering_contributiontobookanthology rendering_harvard rendering_contributiontobookanthology_harvard">van den Brandt, A, Christopher, M, Zangwill, LM, Rezapour, J, Bowd, C, Baxter, SL, Welsbie, DS, Camp, A, Moghimi, S, Do, JL, Weinreb, RN<a rel="Person" href="https://research.tue.nl/en/persons/chris-cp-snijders/" class="link"><span>, Snijders, CCP</span></a> &amp; Westenberg, MA 2020, <a rel="ContributionToBookAnthology" href="https://research.tue.nl/en/publications/glance-visual-analytics-for-monitoring-glaucoma-progression/" class="link harvard_title"><span>GLANCE: Visual Analytics for Monitoring Glaucoma Progression</span></a>. in B Kozlikova, M Krone, N Smit, DW Fellner, W Hansmann, W Purgathofer &amp; F Sillion (eds), <em>EG VCBM 2020 - Eurographics Workshop on Visual Computing for Biology and Medicine, Full and Short Paper Proceedings.</em> Eurographics Association, pp. 85-96, 2020 Eurographics Workshop on Visual Computing for Biology and Medicine, VCBM 2020, Tübingen, Germany, <span class="date">28/09/20</span>. <a onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank','noopener,noreferrer'); return false;" href="https://doi.org/10.2312/vcbm.20201175" class="link"><span>https://doi.org/10.2312/vcbm.20201175</span></a></div>
            </div>
        
            <div id="cite-standard" class="tab " role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-4" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_standard rendering_contributiontobookanthology rendering_standard rendering_contributiontobookanthology_standard"><a rel="ContributionToBookAnthology" href="https://research.tue.nl/en/publications/glance-visual-analytics-for-monitoring-glaucoma-progression/" class="link"><span><strong>GLANCE: Visual Analytics for Monitoring Glaucoma Progression.</strong></span></a> / van den Brandt, A.; Christopher, Mark; Zangwill, Linda M. et al. <br />EG VCBM 2020 - Eurographics Workshop on Visual Computing for Biology and Medicine, Full and Short Paper Proceedings. ed. / Barbora Kozlikova; Michael Krone; Noeska Smit; Dieter W. Fellner; Werner Hansmann; Werner Purgathofer; Francois Sillion. Eurographics Association, 2020. p. 85-96.<p class="type"><span class="type_family">Research output<span class="type_family_sep">: </span></span><span class="type_classification_parent">Chapter in Book/Report/Conference proceeding<span class="type_parent_sep"> › </span></span><span class="type_classification">Conference contribution</span><span class="type_classification"><span class="type_parent_sep"> › </span>Academic</span><span class="type_classification"><span class="type_parent_sep"> › </span>peer-review</span></p></div>
            </div>
        
            <div id="cite-RIS" class="tab " role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-5" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
                <div class="rendering rendering_researchoutput  rendering_researchoutput_ris rendering_contributiontobookanthology rendering_ris rendering_contributiontobookanthology_ris"><p>TY  - GEN</p><p>T1  - GLANCE</p><p>T2  - 2020 Eurographics Workshop on Visual Computing for Biology and Medicine, VCBM 2020</p><p>AU  - van den Brandt, A.</p><p>AU  - Christopher, Mark</p><p>AU  - Zangwill, Linda M.</p><p>AU  - Rezapour, Jasmin</p><p>AU  - Bowd, Christopher</p><p>AU  - Baxter, Sally L.</p><p>AU  - Welsbie, Derek S.</p><p>AU  - Camp, Andrew</p><p>AU  - Moghimi, Sasan</p><p>AU  - Do, Jiun L.</p><p>AU  - Weinreb, Robert N.</p><p>AU  - Snijders, Chris C.P.</p><p>AU  - Westenberg, Michel A.</p><p>PY  - 2020</p><p>Y1  - 2020</p><p>N2  - Deep learning is increasingly used in the field of glaucoma research. Although deep learning models can achieve high accuracy, issues with trust, interpretability, and practical utility form barriers to adoption in clinical practice. In this study, we explore whether and how visualizations of deep learning-based measurements can be used for glaucoma management in the clinic. Through iterative design sessions with ophthalmologists, vision researchers, and manufacturers of optical coherence tomography (OCT) instruments, we distilled four main tasks, and designed a visualization tool that incorporates a visual field (VF) prediction model to provide clinical decision support in managing glaucoma progression. The tasks are: (1) assess reliability of a prediction, (2) understand why the model made a prediction, (3) alert to features that are relevant, and (4) guide future scheduling of VFs. Our approach is novel in that it considers utility of the system in a clinical context where time is limited. With use cases and a pilot user study, we demonstrate that our approach can aid clinicians in clinical management decisions and obtain appropriate trust in the system. Taken together, our work shows how visual explanations of automated methods can augment clinicians' knowledge and calibrate their trust in DL-based measurements during clinical decision making.</p><p>AB  - Deep learning is increasingly used in the field of glaucoma research. Although deep learning models can achieve high accuracy, issues with trust, interpretability, and practical utility form barriers to adoption in clinical practice. In this study, we explore whether and how visualizations of deep learning-based measurements can be used for glaucoma management in the clinic. Through iterative design sessions with ophthalmologists, vision researchers, and manufacturers of optical coherence tomography (OCT) instruments, we distilled four main tasks, and designed a visualization tool that incorporates a visual field (VF) prediction model to provide clinical decision support in managing glaucoma progression. The tasks are: (1) assess reliability of a prediction, (2) understand why the model made a prediction, (3) alert to features that are relevant, and (4) guide future scheduling of VFs. Our approach is novel in that it considers utility of the system in a clinical context where time is limited. With use cases and a pilot user study, we demonstrate that our approach can aid clinicians in clinical management decisions and obtain appropriate trust in the system. Taken together, our work shows how visual explanations of automated methods can augment clinicians' knowledge and calibrate their trust in DL-based measurements during clinical decision making.</p><p>UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/85146199388</p><p>U2  - 10.2312/vcbm.20201175</p><p>DO  - 10.2312/vcbm.20201175</p><p>M3  - Conference contribution</p><p>SP  - 85</p><p>EP  - 96</p><p>BT  - EG VCBM 2020 - Eurographics Workshop on Visual Computing for Biology and Medicine, Full and Short Paper Proceedings</p><p>A2  - Kozlikova, Barbora</p><p>A2  - Krone, Michael</p><p>A2  - Smit, Noeska</p><p>A2  - Fellner, Dieter W.</p><p>A2  - Hansmann, Werner</p><p>A2  - Purgathofer, Werner</p><p>A2  - Sillion, Francois</p><p>PB  - Eurographics Association</p><p>Y2  - 28 September 2020 through 1 October 2020</p><p>ER  - </p></div>
            </div>
        
